"&#xa0;\nWWC0026                                                            Written evidence submitted by NASUWT &#xa0;\nThe \nNASUWT\n’s submission sets out the \nUnion\n’s views on the key issues identified by the Committee in the terms of reference for the Inquiry. The \nsubmission looks at definitions of the terms \n‘white’ and ‘working class’,\n considers the reasons for the underachievement of white working\n-\nclass children\n, outlines key things that \nthe \nGovernment should be doing to address the issue and highlights some of the critical factors underpinning successful wo\nrk in schools to improve educational outcomes for white working\n-\nclass children.\n&#xa0;\nThe \nNASUWT\n would be happy to give oral evidence to the Select Committee.\n&#xa0;\nThe \nNASUWT\n is the largest teach\ners’\n union representing teachers and school leaders in the \nUK\n.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe extent of white working-class pupils’ educational underachievement and the factors responsible for their underachievement&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nReasons for white working-class underachievement&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe Government’s role in delivering improved educational outcomes for white working-class pupils&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSteps that can be taken to improve the educational outcomes of white working-class pupils&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSeptember 2013\n&#xa0;\n Strand, Steve (2007), \nMinority Ethnic Pupils in the Longitudinal Study of Young People in \nEngland\n.\n DCSF Research Report RR-002. Department for Children, Schools and Families, \nLondon\n.\n Gillborn, David and Kirton, Alison (2000), \nWhite Heat: racism, underachievement and white wor\nking class boys.\n International Journal of Inclusive Education, 4(4) pp 271-288.\n Lewis, Kirstin and Demie, Feyisa (2010), \nRaising the Achievement of White Working Class Pupils: School Strategies\n, \nLondon\n: \nLondon\n Borough of Lambeth.\n Sveinsson, Kjartan Pall, (ed.) (2009,) \nWho Cares about the White Working Class?\n \nLondon\n, \nRunnymede\n Trust.\n Office for National Statistics (ONS), website: \nhttp://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/guide-method/measuring-equality/equality/ethnic-nat-identity-religion/ethnic-group/index.html#1\n \n Department for Education, \nGCSE and Equivalent Attainment by Pupil Characteristics in \nEngland\n, \n2011/12\n, SFR 04/2013.\n Gillborn, David in Sveinsson, Kjartan Pall, (ed.) (2009) op. cit.\n Perry, Emma, and Francis, Becky (December 2010), \nThe Social Class Gap for Educational Achievement: a review of the literature\n, RSA, \nLondon\n.\n Ibid.\n Referenced in \nDemie, Feyisa, and Lewis, Kirstin (2010) \nop.cit.\n Department for Education, \nGCSE and Equivalent Attainment by Pupil Characteristics in \nEngland\n, 2011/12\n, SFR 04/2013.\n \nStrand\n, Steve, (2007),\n op. cit\n.\n OECD (2010), \nPISA 2009 Results: Overcoming Social Bac\nkground\n –\n Equity\n \nin Learning Opportunities and Outcomes, Volume 2\n.\n OECD, Paris.\n Ibid.\n Ibid.\n Ofsted (2013), \nUnseen Children: access and achievement 20 years on – Evidence report.\n Kerr, Kirstin and West, Mel (2010), \nInsight 2: Social inequality: can \nschools narrow the gap?\n, British Educational Research Association (BERA), \nLondon\n.\n Cummings, Colleen; Laing, Karen; Law, James; et al. (April 2012), \nCan Changing Aspirations and Attitudes Impact on Educational Attainment?\n Joseph Rowntree Foundation, York.\n For example, Sveinsson, Kjartan Pall, (ed.) (2009,) op cit. \n OECD (2010), \nPISA 2009 Results: Overcoming Social Backgrounds – Volume II\n, OECD, Paris.\n OECD (2012), \nQuality Matters in Early Childhood Education and Care: \nUnited Kingdom\n (\nEngland\n)\n, OECD, \nParis.\n DWP/DCSF/HM Treasury (2008), \nEnding Child Poverty: Everybody’s Business, \nLondon\n: TSO.\n Cummi